@node "ur4" "HyperAnsi"

@{fg shine} HyperAnsi@{fg text}

 HyperAnsi allows you to make your own, or colour your ansi drawings,
ansi is a form of ascii but with colour and for you that don't know
what ascii is it is basically text. Today ascii is ascii art and is what
you would call big letters, a bit below this review you can see an example
of ascii.

 Hyperansi gets the job done well although I have seen other programs
that allow you to use a paint option where as this doesn't so it can
become a little hard to design your asciis and take longer than other
programs of this kind on the market. The best thing about this is it
saves you so much time when you are colouring ansis in. If you've ever
used BBSes you'll know they contain many fancy coloured ansis and for
you that design them it is a real pain typing the colour escape codes in
by hand. With HyperAnsi you just select your colour and type away then
your ansi will be in whatever colour you selected.

 Here is an example of an ascii :-

   ___________    ________
   \_ _       \__/        \
    //   /    /  \   /    /
  _/       _//   /  /  _//
.-\____/____/ _//_______/---aMIGA iNFORMATION oNLINE---.
`---------/____/-gt^sy---------------------------------'

 It may not look exactly right but to see it properly load AIO issue 13
up into a text editor to see it. This was done by Gribbet of the group
Synaptic. It is a logo for AIO as you can probably see. It has no colour
but could easily be coloured in in HyperAnsi to look better.

 Overall HyperAnsi is very useful to colour in your text, it will save
you plenty of time but lacks some features of other similar programs.

