@node "fe1" "Telnet"

@{fg shine} Begginers guide to telnet@{fg text}

 Telnet is a system that allows you to connect to online terminal systems
while you are on the internet. You can log into shells, bbses and other
online text terminals, probably even some basic muds etc. For this article
I am going to focuss on the connection to bullitain board systems (BBS)
which if you've been a reader for a while you probably know i go on about
them alot so it is a subject of interest for me.
 
 One of the main benifits of telnet is allowing connection to bbses through
the internet, no doubt many of the regular bbs goers that are reading
dread when the phone bill arives as long distance calls to bbses can lift
up a hefty phone bill if you don't get free calls like some countrys. The
price of calling national or international bullitain boards is probably
one of the main causes to the dimise of bbses on a whole as the internet
is much cheaper with ISPs being at a local call or for USA or countrys like
that even a free call. While on the net either web pages, irc, ftp or
whatever you can connect to a bullitain board that maybe on the other
side of the world and you are still being charged a local call or whatever
it costs you to dial up the internet.

 The two main disadvantages are one that it is really slow and not even
half as fast if you called through dialup and the next is that the sysop
of the BBS either has to have an ISDN line to have 24hr connection or
the bbs will only be on telnet access at certain times to keep the sysops
phone bill down aswell. Telnet is alot slower than normal bbs access and
can become a pain but if you can put up with that you can really cut your
phone bill down by telnetting to your favourite boards insted of calling
them up via a terminal package etc.

 To get onto a telnet bbs you are obviously going to have to have internet
access, next you will need a telnet package, you can use normal terminal
packages like term, termite and ncomm but it will take some settings changes
and the results are never as good as a specificly programmed telnet
program. There are about 3 good telnet packages around, AmTerm, DCtelnet
and Virterm, for this article we are going to concentrate on DCtelnet which
is probably the best, you may be wary of using this as it is produced by
the group Digital Corruption and many comments have been made by Holger
Kruse about this being a backdoor program to allow Digital Corruption
members into your computer. I personally don't believe it is a backdooring
program as i have been using it for over 6 months with no problems at all
but if you don't want to use this software then that is up to you.
 
 Anyway, load up DCtelnet and goto the menu, it won't take any setting
up so you go into the menu option 'connection' once the menu has scrolled
down you will see connect, highlight it and let go. A small window will
pop up asking you to enter the ip of whatever, but in this case the 
BBS ip. If you don't know where to find the ip ask the sysop what it is
and he will give you a 4 sectioned code which will look like this but
with different numbers.

                       194.94.83.43

 Some sections of that code may contain 3 numbers insted of just two but
don't worry it is still the same. Enter that number into the box on
dctelnet and press return, it will begin to connect to the telnet bbs,
if there are no nodes free you will get the message

'There are no free units available to service your connection at this 
time.  Please try again later.'

 Otherwise you will connect and the BBS will come up, it is just the
same as a normal bbs but you will notice the speed difference, depending
on the time of day and where the BBS is located can effect the speed,
if you connect early morning to a BBS local to you it sometimes goes
the speed of a normal BBS but at othertimes it will be slow.

 I hope this has got a few of you into telnetting to BBSes but if you
need any more help or have any questions please forward them to

                            @{b}aio@freedom.usa.com@{ub}

@{b}Article By :@{ub} Chris Seward

